05295nam a22006375i 9781847422996DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20072007xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a9781847422996  a(DE-B1597)646300  a(OCoLC)476249794  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcGB-BST 4aH97 7aPOL0280002bisacsh00aPolicy reconsidered :bMeanings, politics and practices /ced. by Susan M. Hodgson, Zoë Irving. 1aBristol : bPolicy Press, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tNotes on the contributors -- tPolicy and its exploration -- tMeanings -- tThe meaning of policy/policy as meaning -- tPolicy and ‘the good society’ -- tCategorising and policy making -- tPolitics -- tLanguage, politics and values -- tBusiness, power, policy and politics -- t(Social) Policy and politics at the international level -- tPractices -- tEthics, research and policy -- tUser involvement -- tPolicies as translation: situating transnational social policies -- tStudying policy: a way forward -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe idea of policy is ripe for critical reappraisal. Whilst the context for policy making changes constantly, multiple questions endure, such as how policy is conceived and why; what is taken for granted and what gets problematised; and how policy should be informed, analysed and understood. This book identifies key topics within the policy arena and subjects them to theoretical and practical analysis. It explores the meaning and framing of policy, and examines its practice from the micro- to the supra-national levels, using illustrative case studies to demonstrate how policy is contested, shaped and accounted for. Given the significance of policy as a means to organise and direct social, economic and political life, this book presents the case for a critical restatement of its origins, development and form - without which we risk being caught up in a cycle of change without understanding why or how. The book presents a productive encounter between the three themes of meanings, politics and practices, themes normally not brought together in a single text. It emphasizes the multiplicity of perspectives that can be directed towards understanding the policy world, opening up new ground as well as visiting anew some familiar terrain. Targeted at upper undergraduate and postgraduate students and their teachers, it will also be of interest to researchers and policy actors wanting insight to their project.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aPolicy sciences. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aBoxall, Kathy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBritton, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChau, Ruby C.M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCowburn, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeacon, Bob, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarnsworth, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGregory, Marilyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodgson, Susan M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHodgson, Susan M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIrving, Zoë, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIrving, Zoë, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJenkins, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLendvai, Noémi, econtributor